questions.text: What does a point on a production possibility curve for an economy represent?
choices: maximum output possible with current technology
total demand for goods and services

questions.text:
The diagram shows the production possibility curve (PPC) for an economy producing consumer goods and capital goods.  

The economy is currently producing OM consumer goods and OG capital goods. It decides to increase production of capital goods to OH. What is the opportunity cost of this decision in terms of consumer goods?
What is most likely to increase enterprise as a factor of production in an economy?
choices: a decrease in government spending on education
a decrease in regulation on firms
an increase in taxation on firms

questions.text: Economists describe resources as being scarce. What must be a consequence of scarce resources?
What is the cause of scarcity in an economy?
Which economic activity would be classified as macroeconomics?
choices: households spend less on holidays abroad
income tax is increased by the government
world coffee price rises due to poor weather

questions.text: The diagram shows the effect of a decrease in price on the demand for a product.  What does the arrow on the diagram illustrate?
What is the correct formula to calculate price elasticity of supply?
choices: the percentage change in price divided by the change in quantity supplied
the percentage change in price divided by the percentage change in quantity supplied
the percentage change in quantity supplied divided by the change in price
the percentage change in quantity supplied divided by the percentage change in price

questions.text: What is the most likely cause of a product having a price elasticity of demand greater than one?
choices: The product has a close substitute
The product is a habit-forming good
The product requires only a small proportion of consumer income

questions.text:
For some illnesses, wearing a face mask has a benefit as it could prevent people from getting infected. Not all people are willing to wear face masks. 

Based on the statement above, why would there be an inefficient allocation of face masks in the free market?
choices: Consumers in the free market only consider private costs and benefits.
Face masks are non-rival and non-excludable.
There is abuse of monopoly power by the producer of face masks.
There is perfect information in the free market.
